WEBVTT
Kind: captions

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.080 position:63% line:0%
I am back with another video on scripting.&nbsp;
There are many useful things I could not cover&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:09.640 position:63% line:0%
in the last one, so I will go over more specific&nbsp;
segments in additional videos, but in this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:14.960 position:63% line:0%
I will tell you about a few small nuances&nbsp;
that were left out, but could be very useful.

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:20.840 position:63% line:0%
Let’s start by examining script permissions&nbsp;
in more detail. When you add a script, owner,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:26.640 position:63% line:0%
policy, and the dont-require-permissions&nbsp;
properties are set automatically. The owner&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:33.000 position:63% line:0%
is simply the user who added the script, but&nbsp;
the execution is not limited to that user only.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.640 position:63% line:0%
So if I log in as another user with another&nbsp;
administrator account, I can still run it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.640 --> 00:00:45.440 position:63% line:0%
However, the execution will be prevented for users&nbsp;
who do not have full user rights. A read-only&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:51.320 position:63% line:0%
account cannot execute this script even though&nbsp;
it only reads information, but we can change&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:56.640 position:63% line:0%
this by setting the dont-require-permissions&nbsp;
property to yes, and now it can be executed by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.640 --> 00:01:03.360 position:63% line:0%
anyone – even the read-only users who cannot&nbsp;
edit the source. This allows for a very neat&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:10.080 position:63% line:0%
way to give your non-admin users very specific&nbsp;
abilities if you will. But you cannot control&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:16.920 position:63% line:0%
which users will be able to run which scripts&nbsp;
as it is a simple on/off switch for everyone.

00:01:16.920 --> 00:01:23.080 position:63% line:0%
What you can control is the policy, but for most&nbsp;
people and most scripts, it is not necessary to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:28.600 position:63% line:0%
alter it from the default. Theoretically, if you&nbsp;
wrote a very versatile script that could end up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:34.960 position:63% line:0%
executing almost any command, then you could limit&nbsp;
the script's capabilities with the policy, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:40.280 position:63% line:0%
that is not usually the case. Another situation&nbsp;
where I could imagine this property being used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:46.760 position:63% line:0%
is when you have copied a script that you want to&nbsp;
run for some reason, but you don’t understand it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:52.200 position:63% line:0%
Then you could disable certain privileges like&nbsp;
the ability to change the password and access&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:58.520 position:63% line:0%
sensitive information, for example. That is&nbsp;
the sort of stuff you can do with the policy.

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:03.400 position:63% line:0%
Let’s move on to some code quirks.
First up, I should mention that you can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:10.360 position:63% line:0%
comment out lines using the hashtag symbol,&nbsp;
so they don’t get executed when debugging,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:14.840 position:63% line:0%
for example. And of course, you&nbsp;
can add informational comments.

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:19.480 position:63% line:0%
Another quick thing I should mention&nbsp;
is that you can split lines without&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:24.480 position:63% line:0%
breaking the execution. Just go&nbsp;
to one of the spaces and type a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:29.200 position:63% line:0%
backslash followed by enter. You can&nbsp;
do it as many times as necessary,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:35.000 position:63% line:0%
and it can help you tidy things up when you are&nbsp;
exceeding the workable width of your terminal.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:40.800 position:63% line:0%
Now, whenever you press ‘enter’, you&nbsp;
are actually typing an invisible symbol,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:47.880 position:63% line:0%
sometimes called an end-of-line sequence or&nbsp;
just a new-line character. Historically there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:53.680 position:63% line:0%
have been differences between these characters&nbsp;
in different operating systems and Windows has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:59.960 position:63% line:0%
taken a double-character approach. The&nbsp;
same two-character sequence is being used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:06.440 position:63% line:0%
in RouterOS scripts. This could potentially have&nbsp;
an implication when copying and pasting lines of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:14.440 position:63% line:0%
code between different environments or using a&nbsp;
script to access information from somewhere else.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:17.680 position:63% line:0%
If we create a string and we&nbsp;
want to include a newline,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:22.120 position:63% line:0%
we could just press enter, but that&nbsp;
breaks up the line in our script,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:30.160 position:63% line:0%
so alternatively we can also use “\n”. Those two&nbsp;
characters will get interpreted as a newline.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:38.520 position:63% line:0%
Now, the “:put” command is displaying these with a&nbsp;
little tab added, but both newlines are the same.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:44.400 position:63% line:0%
The backslash in strings is used to escape&nbsp;
the typical use of characters. In this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:50.000 position:63% line:0%
it turns the letter ‘n’ into a newline,&nbsp;
but there are several other such cases and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.280 position:63% line:0%
they are known as escape sequences. So, for&nbsp;
example, you can use it to include a double&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.280 --> 00:04:01.360 position:63% line:0%
quote inside of a string, preventing&nbsp;
that symbol from ending the string.

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:06.240 position:63% line:0%
Similarly, you can include the backslash&nbsp;
itself into a string and so on.&nbsp;

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:14.640 position:63% line:0%
You can even include specific hex values&nbsp;
of symbols, so 4D and 54 can become… MT.&nbsp;

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:18.640 position:63% line:0%
Moving on, it is possible to&nbsp;
concatenate or combine strings.&nbsp;

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:22.760 position:63% line:0%
All you have to do is place a simple&nbsp;
dot between them. Alternatively,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:29.280 position:63% line:0%
you can also combine some text with a variable.&nbsp;
If one of those variables is of a different kind,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:34.800 position:63% line:0%
like a number or boolean, it will still&nbsp;
work, as long as the output is text.

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:39.120 position:63% line:0%
The last thing that I would like to&nbsp;
touch on is command substitution. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:43.720 position:63% line:0%
already showed you in the last video, that&nbsp;
you can execute multiple operations in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:47.880 position:63% line:0%
brackets and that the dollar sign,&nbsp;
which is used to call variables,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:53.600 position:63% line:0%
can also be used before brackets to&nbsp;
perform operations inside of a string.

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:55.240 position:63% line:0%
But what you might not realize,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.240 --> 00:05:01.840 position:63% line:0%
is that we also have the square brackets&nbsp;
which can be used to substitute commands.&nbsp;

00:05:01.840 --> 00:05:06.680 position:63% line:0%
Here is what it looks like. The first string will&nbsp;
get its value assigned from the output of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:13.320 position:63% line:0%
identity print command. But the second string&nbsp;
will have the “get” command called inside it.&nbsp;

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:19.320 position:63% line:0%
So now if we run the script, we can see that&nbsp;
the output is a simple identity print followed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:26.280 position:63% line:0%
by a sentence containing a specific MAC address&nbsp;
that was inserted using the command substitution.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:29.760 position:63% line:0%
Alright, that is enough information&nbsp;
for this video. If you are interested&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:35.280 position:63% line:0%
in scripting, stay tuned as there&nbsp;
are a couple more videos coming soon.

